				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Here ya go Xuthaz -
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I understand your point. My point was that the dual wield issue caused us to have to rebalance all of the pets. When we were in the process of doing this,<span style="font-weight: bold"> mage pets got their dual wield and became the top pet we would give anyone based upon their combat performance.</span> Everyone else had to be lower than that. The next was necromancer pets. The change affected them to a pretty large degree, so we added the lifetap proc. Shaman pets weren't affected at all since they never dual wielded. Enchanter pets were affected, but we determined that the pet ended
<br />
up where it should be in the new scheme of things.
<br />
Now, with the necromancer, we found that though their pet fit in the
<br />
proper place, the change had reduced the combined power of the necromancer too much. We therefore added the additional spells to their class. With enchanters, we decided that the total "power" of the class
<br />
was not reduced far enough to warrant any reimbursement for the change in weapons delay. This is primarily because when then enchanter was balanced, it was not balanced with a pet. The pet was introduced post-production in order to deal with a balance issue at lower levels. This is why they aren't a "pet class".
<br />

<br />
-Gordon</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
